{"id":"nlin/0512014","submitter":"Tony Roberts","authors":"A. J. Roberts","title":"Use the information dimension, not the Hausdorff","comments":"11 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.PS","license":null,"abstract":"  Multi-fractal patterns occur widely in nature. In developing new algorithms\nto determine multi-fractal spectra of experimental data I am lead to the\nconclusion that generalised dimensions $D_q$ of order $q\\leq0$, including the\nHausdorff dimension, are effectively \\emph{irrelevant}. The reason is that\nthese dimensions are extraordinarily sensitive to regions of low density in the\nmulti-fractal data. Instead, one should concentrate attention on generalised\ndimensions $D_q$ for $q\\geq 1$, and of these the information dimension $D_1$\nseems the most robustly estimated from a finite amount of data.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 7 Dec 2005 05:38:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
